    "body": "It's cool, I understand. Still, if\n\n```\nx[('a',)]\n```\n\nis interpreted as\n\n```\nx[('a', '')]\n```\n\nit would be great if MultiIndex.from_tuples() did the same transformation, i.e. from ('a',) to ('a', '').\n\nWhat I was really trying to do is creating a MultiIndex from a mixed set of strings and tuples:\n\n```\ntest = MultiIndex.from_tuples(['a', ('b', 'c'), ('b', 'd'), 'e'])\n```\n\nAs far as I understand, it is interpreted as\n\n```\ntest = MultiIndex.from_tuples([('a',), ('b', 'c'), ('b', 'd'), ('e',)])\n```\n\nHow can I easily to what makes sense without having to revert to something like this?\n\n```\n>>> test = MultiIndex.from_tuples([('b', 'c'), ('b', 'd')])\n>>> x = DataFrame(0, index=['row1'], columns=test)\n>>> x['a'] = 0\n>>> x\n      b     a\n      c  d   \nrow1  0  0  0\n\n[1 rows x 3 columns]\n>>> x.columns\nMultiIndex(levels=[[u'b', u'a'], [u'c', u'd', u'']],\n           labels=[[0, 0, 1], [0, 1, 2]])\n```\n"
  },
